The translation matrix question is central to determining the pose. While experimenting with the `Transform3d` helps identify the correct mount angles, especially when using the cartoonish representation of the robot and target with numerical poses, adjustments might still be needed based on actual measurements. 

Creating a `PhotonPoseEstimator` requires specifying the `Transform3d` representing the robot-relative location and orientation of the camera. This `Transform3d` comprises a `Translation3d` (in meters) and a `Rotation3d` (in radians). For more details on the coordinate system, refer to [Coordinate Systems](https://docs.photonvision.org/en/latest/docs/aprilateral-pipelines/coordinate-systems.html).

A common setup initializes this transform as:
```java
public static final Transform3d kRobotToCam = new Transform3d(
    new Translation3d(0.5, 0.0, 0.5),
    new Rotation3d(0, 0, 0)
);
```
